---
# ============================================================
# Project Requirements Document
# Multi-Tenant RAG Chat Platform
# ============================================================

project:
  name: "Multi-Tenant RAG Chat Platform"
  version: "1.0.0 — PoC"
  status: draft
  created: "2026-04-01"
  authors: ["Platform Engineering"]

# ============================================================
# Overview
# ============================================================

overview:
  description: >
    A multi-tenant conversational RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) platform
    that allows multiple organisations (tenants) to deploy isolated AI chat
    assistants backed by their own knowledge base. Each tenant's assistant
    responds strictly within the bounds of its indexed documentation.
    A single shared codebase serves all tenants — differentiated at runtime
    by tenantId injected as an environment variable into the UI.

  objectives:
    - Single codebase, multiple tenant deployments
    - Per-tenant knowledge base isolation — agents cannot cross tenant boundaries
    - Persistent session and conversation history in Aurora PostgreSQL
    - File upload support within a conversation session (multi-turn)
    - Guardrails enforce KB-scoped answers only (no hallucination from training data)
    - Fully automated infrastructure provisioning via AWS CDK (TypeScript)
    - Streaming responses for real-time chat UX
    - Simple auth for PoC — no-auth or Google OAuth

  non_goals:
    - Real-time knowledge capture (KaCey-style SME interviewing)
    - BOM extraction or document processing pipelines
    - Multi-agent orchestration (single agent per tenant for PoC)
    - Mobile applications
    - On-premise deployment

# ============================================================
# Key Design Decisions
# ============================================================

decisions:
  - id: DEC-001
    question: "Full TypeScript stack vs .NET backend?"
    decision: "Full TypeScript — Nuxt 4 (UI + server routes) + CDK (TypeScript)"
    rationale: >
      One language across UI, server logic, and infrastructure reduces context-switching.
      Nuxt 4 server routes (powered by h3/Nitro) handle API, SSE streaming, and
      database access within the same process and Docker image — no separate service
      needed. AWS SDK v3 for JavaScript/TypeScript is first-class.
      CDK in TypeScript means infra and app share types and config.
    trade_offs:
      - ".NET is more familiar to existing team — learning curve for Nuxt"
      - "Node.js connection pooling for Aurora needs postgres.js carefully configured"
      - "TypeScript CDK is already the norm — no change needed there"

  - id: DEC-002
    question: "Separate API service or Nuxt server routes?"
    decision: "Nuxt server routes — no separate API service"
    rationale: >
      Nuxt 4 server routes (server/api/*.ts) run inside the same Nitro server
      process as the UI. They support SSE streaming, AWS SDK calls, Aurora
      access, and middleware — everything a separate API would do.
      Each tenant gets one ECS task (one Nuxt deployment) with TENANT_ID env var.
      This eliminates a second Docker image, second ECS service, and cross-service
      network calls. Simpler ops, fewer moving parts for PoC.
      Future: if a mobile app or third-party integration needs the API, extract
      server routes into a standalone Hono or Fastify service at that point.
    trade_offs:
      - "UI and server logic are co-located — less separation of concerns"
      - "Cannot share one API across tenant UIs — each tenant has own Nuxt server"
      - "Scaling UI and API independently is not possible — scale as one unit"

  - id: DEC-003
    question: "tenantId source — URL subdomain, path, or env var?"
    decision: "Environment variable TENANT_ID on each UI deployment for PoC"
    rationale: >
      Each Nuxt 4 ECS task is deployed with a different TENANT_ID env var.
      Same Docker image, different config. Simple, no routing logic needed.
      In production: migrate to subdomain routing (tenant.platform.com) on ALB.
    deployment_model:
      poc: "Separate ECS task per tenant UI, same image, different TENANT_ID — accessible via public ALB"
      production: "Single UI ECS service, ALB listener rules by subdomain"

  - id: DEC-004
    question: "Authentication approach for PoC?"
    decision: "Google OAuth via nuxt-google-auth — lightweight, no corporate IdP needed"
    rationale: >
      No-auth is simplest but provides zero userId for session ownership.
      Google OAuth with nuxt-google-auth takes ~2 hours to configure, gives
      real userId (email), and demonstrates auth readiness without a corporate IdP.
      For true no-auth PoC: userId defaults to a browser-generated UUID stored
      in localStorage.
    options:
      no_auth:
        effort: "30 minutes"
        userId_source: "Browser UUID in localStorage"
        risk: "No user isolation — anyone can see any session if they know sessionId"
      google_oauth:
        effort: "2 hours"
        userId_source: "Google email from JWT"
        risk: "Requires Google OAuth app registration"

  - id: DEC-005
    question: "Session storage — DynamoDB or Aurora?"
    decision: "Aurora PostgreSQL (same cluster as vector store)"
    rationale: >
      Aurora Serverless v2 is already required for Bedrock KB vector storage.
      Using it for sessions avoids a second service. Relational schema is
      simpler to query (history, search, audit). Bedrock KB uses RDS Data API
      (HTTP, stateless) so it does not compete with the Nuxt server connection pool.
      Connection pooling from Nuxt server routes managed by postgres.js pool (max 25).

  - id: DEC-006
    question: "Aurora topology — shared cluster or per-tenant cluster?"
    decision: "Shared Aurora Serverless v2 cluster, separate schema per tenant"
    rationale: >
      One cluster scales to near-zero ACU when idle (dev/PoC cost ~$0).
      Tenant isolation via PostgreSQL schemas (vectors_acme, vectors_contoso, etc.)
      and tenant_id column in app schema tables. Bedrock KB RdsConfiguration
      specifies schema.table per tenant. One cluster, N schemas, one backup.

  - id: DEC-007
    question: "Bedrock Agent per tenant or shared agent with metadata filter?"
    decision: "One Bedrock Agent per tenant"
    rationale: >
      Separate agents provide hard isolation — agent instructions, KB
      association, and guardrails are all scoped per tenant. No risk of
      cross-tenant KB retrieval from misconfigured metadata filter. New tenant
      = new agent in CDK TenantStack loop.

  - id: DEC-008
    question: "Is per-tenant ECS service the right long-term architecture?"
    decision: "Acceptable for PoC — must be revisited before production"
    scaling_note:
      - "Per-tenant ECS service is PoC-only: simple to deploy, easy to isolate for validation"
      - "Production architecture will move to a single shared ECS service with tenant routing"
      - "Tenant resolved via subdomain (acme.platform.example.com) + ALB listener rules in future"
      - "tenantId injected server-side from subdomain match — eliminates N ECS services"
      - "Bedrock Agent isolation and Aurora schema isolation are unaffected by this change"

  - id: DEC-009
    question: "Is direct database access acceptable during development?"
    decision: "Yes — authenticated direct DB access is permitted in dev/PoC environments only"
    rationale: >
      Direct Aurora access (via a PostgreSQL client such as psql, TablePlus, or DBeaver)
      removes friction during early development. Schema changes, query debugging, and data
      inspection are significantly faster without going through a service layer.
      This is a speed-for-learning tradeoff, not a weakening of production security standards.
    scope: "dev and PoC environments only — never production"
    guardrails:
      - "Access requires authentication — IAM database authentication or Secrets Manager credentials; no shared passwords"
      - "Connect only to dev/test Aurora cluster — production cluster credentials are never shared with developers"
      - "No real customer or production data in dev/PoC environments"
      - "No cross-tenant schema access unless explicitly granted for a specific test scenario and revoked after"
      - "Prefer read-only roles for exploratory access; use write access only when actively developing schema or seed data"
      - "Access via AWS Session Manager port-forward where possible — avoids exposing Aurora to the public internet"
      - "All connections logged via Aurora audit log (best-effort for PoC; enforced for production)"
    transition:
      trigger: "Before any production deployment or when non-synthetic data enters the system"
      replace_with:
        - "All data access mediated through Nuxt server routes / service layer"
        - "Tenant-aware authorization enforced at service level (tenantId always from server-side config)"
        - "Database credentials restricted to application service account only"
        - "Schema migrations managed via CDK or a migration tool (e.g. node-pg-migrate) — no ad-hoc DDL"
        - "Direct developer access to production Aurora requires a break-glass process with audit trail"

# ============================================================
# Architecture
# ============================================================

architecture:
  diagram: |

    ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
    │  Tenant: acme                        Tenant: contoso             │
    │  TENANT_ID=acme                      TENANT_ID=contoso           │
    │  Nuxt 4 (UI + server routes)         Nuxt 4 (UI + server routes) │
    │  ECS Fargate task                    ECS Fargate task            │
    │  acme.platform.example.com           contoso.platform.example.com│
    │                                                                  │
    │  server/api/chat.post.ts    ←──────── All API logic lives here   │
    │  server/api/sessions.get.ts           Same Docker image          │
    │  server/api/sessions.post.ts          Different TENANT_ID env    │
    └──────────┬───────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────┘
               │                                   │
               ↓                                   ↓
    ┌──────────────────────┐           ┌───────────────────────┐
    │  Bedrock Agent       │           │  Aurora Serverless v2 │
    │  (per tenant)        │           │  (shared cluster)     │
    │                      │           │                       │
    │  acme-agent          │           │  schema: app          │
    │  contoso-agent       │           │    sessions           │
    │                      │           │    messages           │
    │  ↓ KB Retrieval      │           │                       │
    │  ↓ Guardrails        │           │  schema: vectors_acme │
    │  ↓ 1hr session mem   │           │    bedrock_kb         │
    └──────────┬───────────┘           │                       │
               ↓                       │  schema: vectors_cont │
    ┌──────────────────────┐           │    bedrock_kb         │
    │  Bedrock KB          │           └───────────────────────┘
    │  (per tenant)        │
    │  acme-kb / cont-kb   │
    │  ↑ RDS Data API      │
    └──────────┬───────────┘
               ↓
    ┌───────────────────────┐
    │  S3 Buckets           │
    │  (per tenant)         │
    │  acme-docs / cont-docs│
    └───────────────────────┘

  components:
    nuxt_app:
      name: "Nuxt 4 (UI + Server Routes)"
      runtime: "Node.js 22 (SSR via Nitro)"
      deployment: "ECS Fargate — one task per tenant"
      image: "Same Docker image, different TENANT_ID env var"
      ui: "Vue 3 pages + components (Nuxt UI v3 / shadcn-vue)"
      server: "Nitro server routes in server/api/ — Bedrock, Aurora, SSE"

    bedrock_agents:
      description: "One agent per tenant"
      model: "anthropic.claude-3-haiku-20240307-v1:0"
      session_ttl: "1 hour (active working memory)"

    bedrock_kb:
      description: "One KB per tenant"
      embedding_model: "amazon.titan-embed-text-v2:0"
      vector_dimensions: 1024
      vector_store: "Aurora pgvector (per-tenant schema)"

    guardrails:
      description: "Shared guardrail policy (can be overridden per tenant)"
      grounding_threshold: 0.75
      relevance_threshold: 0.75

    database:
      engine: "Aurora Serverless v2 (PostgreSQL 16)"
      min_acu: 0
      max_acu: 4
      topology: "Shared cluster, separate schemas per tenant"
      access:
        api: "postgres.js connection pool (max 25, TCP)"
        bedrock_kb: "RDS Data API (HTTP, stateless)"

    storage:
      description: "One S3 bucket per tenant for documents"

